h3. Issue Summary
When we are creating JIRA issues from Confluence, custom fields we create on JIRA show up in the form of issue creation. Though, if there is a custom field using radio buttons that is set as required for that project/issue type, Confluence doesn't allow us to create it.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# [Create a custom field on JIRA|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiracloud/create-a-custom-field-991923727.html] - make sure to be radio buttons style;
# Make this custom field [required|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiracloud/changing-a-field-configuration-844500798.html] in the project;
# Go to Confluence and edit/create a page;
# Call the */jira* macro;
# In the JIRA macro modal, select *Create New Issue*;
# Pick the project and issue type you associated the custom field on JIRA.

h3. Expected Results
As any other custom field created on JIRA, you are able to proceed with the issue creation.

h3. Actual Results
The message "_The required field *CUSTOM_FIELD_NAME* is not available in this form. You will need to create your issue directly in JIRA._"

h3. Workaround
Let the custom field as optional on JIRA.

h3. Issue Summary
The new feature of archiving pages is awesome, as it allows us to administer our pages in a better way. 
Though, when we have a link to a page we just archived, exporting this page to HTML will bring the archived page in the zip file, but when clicking on the link to this page, it won't work.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page called *To Archive* and publish it;
# Copy *To Archive*'s URL;
# Create a new page called *The Page*  and paste the link;
# Publish it;
# Move *To Archive* to under *The Page*, just to make the understanding of this bug easier;
# Go to *Space Settings > Content Tools > Export*;
# Select *HTML* option;
# Select the custom option and pick *The Page*;
# Export it and download the zip;
# Open *The Page* HTML file and click over the *To Archive* link.


h3. Expected Results
The browser opens the *To Archive* HTML file.

h3. Actual Results
File not found is shown.

*Notes* 
* It is weird that the *To Archive* HTML is there and accessible if you open it separately.

h3. Workaround
Open the HTML file of the page separately or restore the pages before performing the export.

h3. Issue Summary

If you try to update a page body that includes links to other confluence pages via REST API, this fails returning status code 400 (bad request) and below message:
{quote}com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: Content body cannot be converted to new editor format
{quote}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page containing a link to another page
 # GET the page content via REST API expanding the body in storage format. E.g.
{noformat}
https://<NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/<PAGE-ID>?expand=body.storage
{noformat}

 # Use the body returned from previous step to update the page sending a PUT request to
{noformat}
https://<NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/<PAGE-ID>
{noformat}

h3. Expected Results

The page gets successfully updated
h3. Actual Results

The update fails and below error is returned:
{noformat}
{{{"statusCode": 400,"data": {"authorized": false,"valid": true,"errors": [],"successful": false},"message": "com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: Content body cannot be converted to new editor format"}}}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

The root-cause for this issue seems to be that for some reason the tag *{{ri:space-key}}* is expected to be found even if:
 - It is not returned in the storage representation of the link when sending the GET request (step 2):
{noformat}
<ac:link><ri:page ri:content-title=\"NEW TEST\" ri:version-at-save=\"6\" /></ac:link>
{noformat}

 - It is not mandatory and not even needed most of the time

 

Indeed, even if this is not even documented for the links storage format in [Confluence Storage Format - Links|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/confluence-storage-format-790796544.html#ConfluenceStorageFormat-Links] (for Server but still applicable), it can be found in the examples on the same page:
{quote}AN EXAMPLE OF DIFFERENT LINK BODIES 
{noformat}
<ac:link>
 <!-- Any resource identifier --> 
 <ri:page ri:content-title="Home" ri:space-key="SANDBOX" /> 
 <ac:link-body>Some <strong>Rich</strong> Text</ac:link-body>
 </ac:link>
 ...
{noformat}
{quote}
 

Therefore, by using below format you should manage to update the page:
{noformat}
<ac:link><ri:page ri:content-title=\"NEW TEST\" ri:space-key=\"<SPACE-KEY>\" /></ac:link>
{noformat}
 

You can follow the below thread on the developers community for further updates/discussions on this:
 - [https://community.developer.atlassian.com/t/updating-content-using-rest-api-fails-with-content-body-cannot-be-converted-to-new-editor-format/37624]

h3. Issue Summary
When selecting the *JIRA Report* option while creating a new page and also picking the *Change Log* template, the new page is created with no content.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a new page;
# In the template modal, search for *JIRA Reports*;
# Select the *Change Log* template;
# Create the page.

h3. Expected Results
The new page is filled with the template content and also the content from the project and release you set.

h3. Actual Results
A blank page is created.

h3. Workaround
# Create a new page;
# In the template modal, search for JIRA Reports;
# Select the Change Log template;
# Create the page.
# Publish the (blank) page.
# Edit the page, which should properly display the contents
